"{\"uid\": \"dailypost.ng-2024-06-28-cas-clears-amusan-of-doping-violation-offence-ahead-2024-olympics\", \"text\": \"Published  on  By  Nigeria's Tobi Amusan has been cleared to compete at the 2024 Olympic Games in Paris, DAILY POST reports.  The Court of Arbitration for Sports (CAS) dismissed appeals by the World Athletics (WA) and the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) against the women's 100-metre hurdles world record holder.  The CAF concurred with an earlier verdict by the World Athletics Disciplinary Tribunal (WADT) that found Amusan not guilty of any anti-doping rule violations.  The 28-year-old was suspended last year by the Athletics Integrity Unit (AIU) for missing three drug tests within a 12-month period.  The body sought a two-year period of ineligibility for Amusan.  The suspension was upturned by the AIU, which allowed her to run at the 2023 World Athletics Championship.  This ruling by CAS marks the end of a legal process that began with the WADT's initial decision on August 17, 2023.  Transfer: Chelsea announce departure of two players  Transfer: Man Utd get new assistant coach to support Ten Hag  CAS clears Super Eagles' group opponents Tanzania for AFCON 2025  2025 World Championships: Amusan credits 'God' for silver medal success  CAS promises to protect lives, property as he assesses security infrastructure in Kebbi  Lapses cause air accidents - CAS warns senior commanders against complacency  CAS reaffirms commitment to protecting lives, property against enemy attack  Insecurity: Ensure impact of your presence in Benue is felt - Group to CAS  Copyright \\u00a9Daily Post Media Ltd\"}"